column168: At approximately 3:30pm tank AFIU580607-2 was being moved by equipment operator in the terminal yard in order to load onto truck/chassis for delivery. At the time of lifting, the operator noticed that the tank could not be lifted due to another tank obstructing the lift. Operator proceeded to try and move the tank by slowly lifting and dragging when one of the corner posts of the tank broke and as a result the tank fell to the ground. 911 was called, U.S Coast Guard was notified. No leaks were detected, as precautionary action absorbent material was used to create a perimeter until emergency response units arrived. Fire Dept confirmed no leaks emitting from tank.
column169: Operator will be scheduled for retraining.

column168: Fluid was reported to be dripping from the top of tank car TILX 101279 onto the ground in the UPRR Yard in Arden, NV. column168: During a routine inspection of a van trailer at a Clean harbors TTT location an employee observed a small amount of material leaking from the trailer. Plant Hazmat personnel were notified and responded to the trailer.  Donning appropriate Personsonal Protective Equipment (PPE), made entry into the trailer and initiated moving containers in order to identify the leaking container. It was determined  that the integrity of the 5 gallon container secured to a pallet failed causing it to leak the Corrosive liquid onto the trailer floor. The hazmat team absorb the material off the deck of trailer and the surrounding area and placed both the 5 gallon container and absorbent material into a salvage drum.  The container was sent for disposal to the intended disposal facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the location that offered the shipment for transportation have been instructed to inspect the condition of the containers for integrity prior to offering for transportation.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Manager of Hazardous Materials Matthew Thompson received a report of tank car GATX  212789 leaking from the protective housing. Per information received, there was no determination on the amount of material released. Upon arrival, Manager Thompson found a very small leak of dripping material from the protective housing inspection ports. It was then discovered ,once opening the housing, that the A-End liquid line was leaking around the closure plug. As a result the liquid line was found partially open along with a less than tool tight closure plug. The valve was completly closed and the plug tightened.

One of our fuel delivery trucks was delivering fuel to a customer's above ground storage tank. During delivery the transfer hose burst for unknown reasons and diesel fuel was spilled on the site (approximately 200 gallons). The site is a large industrial parcel with gravel and the fuel was contained on the individual site and did not reach any drains or waterways.     A Hazmat responder was immediately called and environmental staff went to the site. The spill was also reported to the South Carolina Department of  Health and Environmental Controls (SCDHEC). SCDHEC visited the site the day after the incident. Initial amounts of fuel were removed by vacuum truck and excavation of the contaminated soil/gravel followed.    A initial site assessment will be performed by a licensed geologist to confirm remediation.All fuel was disposed of as hazadous waste as required by law. Manifests document proper disposal by the clean up contractor.

column168: On March 7, 2014, at 1742 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Queensgate Terminal, Cincinnati, Ohio noticed an odor near and dripping from the bottom of GATX 29936, a loaded tank car of UN2053,METHYL ISOBUTYL CARBINOL . The tank car was isolated and a spill pan was placed beneath the bottom outlet valve. The shipper, Johann Haltemann, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-03-07-00206. Emergency Management Specialists EMS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Queensgate Terminal. EMS found the bottom outlet valve leaking and suspected a faulty internal valve component which would not stop the release. David Zapata 713- 203-1768, was notified of the situation found. The load had to be transferred into tanker trucks for final disposition. GATX 29936 is awaiting FRA one time movement approval for disposition. This incident did require a special move.    NARRI: 2x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 24  Cause code:551

column168: On 3-12-2014, at 18:00, personnel in the  Terminal Railway (TASD) Interchange discovered TCIX 30009 , a loaded tank car of Fuel Oil, leaking from the Dome. This incident did not require a special switching move.

column168: JCI JONES CHEMICALS, INC. (JCI) DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION TO ITS CUSTOMER BBP WATER CORPORATION IN SPENCER, IN.  AFTER THE CUSTOMER SIGNED OFF ON JCI'S BILL-OF-LADING THAT THE CONNECTION HAD BEEN SECURED TO THE PROPER LINE FOR DISCHARGING INTO THE PROPER TANK, THAT ALL VALVES WERE OPEN AND ABLE TO RECEIVE PRODUCT, AND THAT THE TANK LEVEL WAS AT SUFFICIENT LEVEL TO RECEIVE AND CONTAIN THE QUANTITY OF PRODUCT DESCRIBED ON THE DELIVERY TICKET, JCI'S DRIVER BEGAN TO UNLOAD THE 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK.  AT SOME POINT DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK OVERFILLED.  THE JCI DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF PRODUCT MINIMIZING THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT OVERFLOWED OUT OF THE TANK WHICH WAS ESTIMATED TO BE APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS.  THE CUSTOMER HAS AN OVERFLOW PIPE INSTALLED ON THE TOP OF THEIR TANK WHICH IS WHERE THE PRODUCT CAME OUT OF.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AS A PRECAUTION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR PROPERTY DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THE TANK OVERFLOW.  JCI BELIEVE'S THAT THE SITE GAUGE ON THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK MAY HAVE MALFUNCTIONED CAUSING THE CUSTOMER TO THINK THAT THERE WAS SUFFICIENT ROOM IN THE STORAGE TANK TO RECEIVE ALL OF THE PRODUCT BEING UNLOADED.  PLEASE NOT THAT WE ENTERED "N/A" IN PART III-QUESTION 25 AS JCI'S CARGO TANK WAS NOT THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT NOR DID I FALL IN ANY WAY.
column169: JCI has recommended to its customer that they verify that their site gauge is working properly and to install a new one if it is not. JCI has also recommended that the customer install a high level warning alarm on their storage tank and that their overflow pipe be vented/discharged into a secondary containment device.

column168: THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION. AZER202 DERAILED 5 E BOXCARS AND 3 L SULFURIC ACID CANS ON 3/14/2014 @ 0845 MST. AS THE FIRST TANK CAR CAME OFF THE RAIL, IT BROKE THE DRAW BAR HOUSING AND PUNCTURED A HOLE ON THE B END OF MDCX1396, THE SECOND LOADED ACID CAR. THE CONDUCTOR IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM LISTED ON HIS HAZMAT PAPERWORK AS WELL AS THE DISPATCHER AS SOON AS HE COULD BEE THE MDCX1396 WAS LEAKING AND TO INFORM THEM OF THE DERAILMENT. MDCX1396 SPILLED 13,600 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID ONTO THE GROUND. WITH THE MOW'S QUICK RESPONSE, WE WERE ABLE TO GET A LOADER ON THE SCENE AND CONTAIN THE SPILL BEFORE IT MADE IT TO THE RIVER. THE RAILROAD CONTRACTED H2O ENVIRONMENTAL FOR THE HAZMAT CLEAN UP AND REHABILITATION OF THE AREA. ALL CONTAINMATED SAND WAS CLEANED UP BY THE END OF THE DAY ON 3/19/2014.
column169: THE AZER, ARIZONA EASTERN RAILROAD, IS LOOKING AT HOW WE RUN OUR TRAINS ON THE CLIFTON SUB. WE ARE LOOKING AT POSSIBLY RUNNING MANNED HELPERS TO FACILITATE THE MOVEMENT OF OUR TRAINS FROM LORDSBURG, NM TO CLIFTON, AZ.

The shipment from PAF was loaded on the cargo ship Horizon Consumer 324N out of Tacoma, Wa with a destination of Anchorage,Alaska.  TAG (The Adherence Group) is contracted to perform random inspections on cargo shipment to ensure compliance with the tariff.  Upon inspection container PAFX545062 shipped on booking WB4464912, the inspector discovered two cartons of UN0044 Primers shipped in an overpack that was not listed as hazardous.  There was class 3 flammable UN1263 paint declared on the shipment and billed correctly.  The shipment was held, the customer contacted and new billing was submitted.  The class 1.4S primers were removed from the shipment and the customer picked it up from the port to bring the container shipment back into compliance.  The shipper who provided the shipment to PAF did not declare the primers on their documentation.
column169: Many shippers tendering cargo to freight consolidators are not trained in the requirements of hazmat transportation.  Perhaps, the consolidator need to be provided better information as to the cargo that shippers are tendering to them in an effort to discover if there may possibly be hazardous cargo contained in the shipment.

The cause for this is that the wrong strapping chart for the trailer was provided to Sasol by the carrier.

This cargo shipped from Tacoma Washington to Anchorage Alaska on the Horizon Kodiak 906N on booking WB4457135 and container PAFX545063.  Upon inspection by TAG (The Adherence Group for tariff compliance, the inspector discovered UN3266 whish was loaded in the container along with the other class 3, 8 and 9 cargo but was not listed on the declaration.  The container was placed on hold and TAG notified the shipper of their findings.  The documentation was updated by the shipper and the cargo was released.

column168: A box truck containing hazardous waste arrived at the safety Kleen Des Moines, IA facility for an offload in order to transfer and consolidate its waste onto a van trailer to its intended waste disposal facility. Safety Kleen Des Moines facility personnel noticed that there was a leaking cubic yard super sack container. A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and unloaded the leaking cubic yard super sack; the cubic yard super sack was repacked into drums for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The box truck floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service.
column169: The release was reported to Ted Petersen with the Iowa Department of Natural Resources (515) 281-8694. Per Ted Petersen's direction no further reporting to the state of Iowa was required. At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or breakage was observed. This release was the direct result of improper container selection. The driver will be retrained on proper container selection for liquid waste streams . The shipper was notified and advised to use an appropriate UN rated container for future shipment of this waste stream.

column168: On March 27, 2014. FRA Inspector Tetterton, Donald ID# 87745, Report # 59,found NATX 303182 Bottom outlet valve handle connection to the bottom outlet valve leaking when the bottom outlet valve handle is secured in the closed position.  Bert Feasley of Buffalo Southern Railroad went and checked on leak 3/27/2014 and cleaned up about 2 pints of crude oil that had leaked on to the ties and ballast below bottom outlet valve. Cleaned up oil that was on valve and put down oil wipes to monitor any future leak. Checked on 3/31/2014 found a few drops of oil had leaked since 3/27/2014. Sent email to Shipper Tidal Energy Marketing Inc. Jason Booth jason.booth@tidal-energy.com, who contacted Rescar mobile repair. Rescar #490 inspected NATX 303182 on 4/4/14 and tighten stem packing that was loose. Leak stopped they advised customer to have valve rebuilt.    Received Movement Approval FRA-14040280 for NATX 303182 on April 21 2014 from FRA  Erich P. Rudolph Railroad Safety Specialist (202) 493-6248. The car will be forwarded to the consignee in Hamburg, NY for off-loading. Once offload the residue car will move to a certified repair facility for the necessary repairs.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing; Vapor Valve
column168: On 03/17/2014 at 1430 hours, Yard personnel from the CSX Chicago DivisionBarr Yard Riverdale, IL discovered GATX 206050, a loaded tank car of Alcohol NOS, leaking from the pressure relief device and vacuum relief device. The car was isolated and shipper, Flint Hills Resources, local agencies, and state agencies were notified. CHEMTREC Report number was issued: 2014031700164. Sunpro, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that there was the vapor line threads were defective and the vapor plug not seated in the plug, vacuum relief device not seating properly and pressure relief device not seating properly. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Kurt McMillan Flint Hills Resources. Contractor personnel fixed the problem. The leak was secured and the car was released. The incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 129, 1009, 702    NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 03/08/2014 at 0318hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal W. Springfield Terminal discovered  UPSU603366, a loaded container with one hazmat pkg of UN3109,   ORGANIC PEROXIDE TYPE F LIQUID PEROXYACETIC ACID, 5.2, II, in a 5 gallon pail leaked approx 3gals onto asphalt pavement. The container was isolated and NRC rept#1065757 and MA EMA report# n/a were notified. The shipper, United Parcel Service Inc, was notified by CSXI Cust Svc. EP+S Vermont, CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one 5 gallon pail leaked 3 gallons product due to loadshift and pail damage. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel over-packed damaged pail which secured the leak, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the material. All lading put back in original freight container with proper load/block/brace and released to the shipper.  This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident did not require a Form 7.1.
column169: The shipper has been referred to the Intermodal Loading Guide for proper loading and adqueate blocking/bracing methods to prevent load-shift during rail transportation.

column168: The shipper had originally had this package tendered to a gun dealer. They requested a reroute to a residential address which made a manager suspicious because FedEx Express does not accept firearms from an individual to an individual. So the manager opened the shipment and found both firearms and a small amount of ammunition. As the shipment was not offered by the shipper with any dangerous goods markings, labeling nor with a shipper's declaration, it's believed to be undeclared or hidden DG. FAA agent Jeff Coppock was notified. The shipment was held pending FAA investigation.
column169: I think this was an isolated incident. The shipper was a grieving daughter who has lost her father and was cleaning out his house in anticipation of tenants. Since she had inherited the guns she was trying to ship them back to herself and she didn't realize that ammunition was a dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column168: Tank car TAEX 2387 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area while in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspecting TAEX 2387 reported the leak source was at its vapor valve's bolted flange connection. The responder found all four flange bolt nuts not tool tight by 3/4 turn each. The responder tool tightened these flange nuts and afterwards no further commodity leakage was observed. The spillage on the shell of TAEX 2387 was cleaned. Also, a small amount of accumulated ground spillage under TAEX 2387 was remediated. TAEX 2387 will be held in isolation pending completion of the FRA OTMA process.  On 3/21/2014, TAEX 2387 was reported leaking commodity again while isolated in the BNSF Amarillo railyard. Containment receptacles were placed under TAEX 2387 to capture commodity drips. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting TAEX 2387 reported the leak source was at the liquid valve's flange connection. Further inspection revealed that the liquid valve's flange gasket had split and allowed commodity to escape at this flange connection. A new flange gasket was applied and the liquid valve's flange connection was secured. After securement was completed no further commodity escape was observed at the liquid valve's flange connection. Spillage on TAEX 2387's side shell was cleaned.
column169: No additional comments.

One of 4 1 gallon metal cans found on the Conway dock spilled.  Once it was discovered the spill was cleaned up in house.

Dispatcher [Tom Strickland] received a call from his driver [Vik Behary] notifying him that there had been a Bleach spill at the customer that he was making a delivery to [Gorman PT. ST. Lucie] The driver stated that he had just started pumping into the customers tank [2 minutes] when he noticed Bleach coming from the pipe on the ground. He shut everything down and went into the store and notified the store manager [Carlos]. I called 2 employees to get a bag of Sodium Sulfite, a couple of empty open top drums and a couple of shovels and put it all in the pickup truck. I gave them the address and instructed them to go ahead and I would meet them there. I grabbed a MSDS for Sodium Hypochlorite and the Weight / Reportable Quantity chart and took it with me in the case that the items would be needed. I was also told that Carlos [from Gorman] had contacted EPA. I reported the spill to my superior [Ron Zeigler] and was instructed by him to contact CBI [John Katzor] to meet me at the site so he could evaluate the mitigation of the spill. I ]Evelio] arrived on scene at 1:15PM, John Katzor arrived on scene 1:20PM we conducted the investigation and found that a 2” schedule 80 PVC coupler was cracked all the way around and someone had put a schedule 40 PVC saddle coupler over the cracked schedule 80 PVC coupler. The AUC personnel were instructed to spread Sodium Sulfite over the small area that Bleach had gotten on and to mix up the dirt to be neutralized. Once this was completed dirt samples were pulled and tested for PH, on the other side of the fence the dirt PH readings were 8 [good] on the area where the pipe sat on the ground was a little bit higher so we added a little bit more Sodium Sulfite and mixed it in and pulled another dirt sample, the second sample the PH was 8 [good] John Katzor stated that this was good and no further actions were required. Our installer had been called to go to Gorman and make the necessary repairs on the pipe, the installer arrived at Gorman at 2PM. Installer cut out the coupler and pipe and placed 2 schedule 80 PVC couplers and 12” of schedule 80 PVC pipe and glued everything together. Store manager and my driver were instructed to allow the glue to dry for 30 minutes before the pipe was used. All AUC personnel started back to the plant at approx. 2:30PM.
column169: Corrective action: Instructed the driver that if there is any schedule 40 PVC on the lines that he is pushing product through to the tanks the Branch must be notified and gets approval to off-load product.   • There is to be no schedule 40 PVC used on pipe lines that we off-load Sodium Hypochlorite through. It all must be schedule 80 PVC.  • Repairs to the schedule 80 PVC should only be conducted by our installer [this way we know that the correct material has been used.  Recommendation: Have customers plumbing inspected [by company representative] to make sure that the correct PVC material is being used and customers aren’t making repairs with the wrong PVC material.

column168: Residue tank car GATX 49828 was reported emanating an odor while in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspecting GATX 49828 reported the odor source was at the manway closure with no liquid commodity observed around the base of the manway nozzle. The manway securement bolt/nuts were found tool tight. Inspection of the hard manway gasket installed in the manway lid gasket groove revealed no observable defects, but the odorous residue commodity vapors still escaped from the manway closure as if the gasket was not sealing properly. A manway nozzle gasket was added and applied around the manway nozzle lip to ensure an air tight closure seal at the manway closure. The manway cover was closed and re-secured by 1230 hrs. PDT, 3/12/2014. Afterwards, the commodity odor ebbed and GATX 49828 was released to proceed to its destination.

Driver traveling on 2 lane paved roadway approaching slight left curve. Driver overcorrected to return truck to paved portion of road, causing vehicle to overturn and roll down 25 foot embankment, landing on its side accross a single section of railroad tracks.CMV driver traveling southeast on two lane paved roadway.  Road was fairly level and had a slight left curve.  As driver approached curve, he became distracted searching for an item that had fallen between and behind the driver and passenger seats, in doing so he took his eyes off roadway and did not enter cure correctly.  Right front wheel of vehicle left pavement to shoulder.  As driver attempted to return the vehicle to the road, he overcorrected and lost control.  The vehicle rolled down a 25 foot embankment coming to rest on its side on a section of railroad tracks.  Train movement stopped for 9 hours while vehicle uprighted and repoved from accident scene.  Driver sustained a minor concussion and lacerations as a result of the accident.

column168: On March 12 the first of two boxes of a shipment from Thomas Scientific were received by Battelle; the second box was delivered on March 13.  Each box contained eleven static eliminators containing 500 microcuries each of Po-210.  Neither box was marked as UN2911, as we believe the should have been. The contents of the first box were discovered after opening at the destination facility.  The second box was stopped and opened (taken out of commerce) at a receiving facility where the discovery was made, prior to reaching the final destination.  The UN2911 markings were added to the re-packaged items identified at the receiving facility prior to delivery to the final destination. Based on the fact that both discoveries were made only after opening the packages (i.e., the packages were no longer in transportation) this report probably is unnecessary.  There were no package failures or releases.

column168: After a BNSF's train arrival at the Corpus Christi Terminal RR (CCPN) interchange yard track, the BNSF was notified by CCPN that entrained tank car OFOX 52932 was leaking commodity from its bottom outlet. A catch receptacle was placed under OFOX 52932 to capture dripping commodity. Contract responders inspecting OFOX 52932 reported finding the top operated bottom outlet valve's (TOBOV) operating rod approximately two turns in the open position. The TOBOV was closed which ended the commodity release at the bottom outlet. In addition, the packing gland nut (PGN) at the TOBOV's operating rod was one full turn less that tool tight. The bottom outlet's closure cap (BOC) was also one full turn from being tool tight thus allowing commodity to escape. The PGN and the BOC were tool tightened to full securement. The captured spillage was transferred to a disposal drum and earmarked for appropriate disposal.

column168: On 07Mar14 at 22:46 while stacking DG cargo onto a plastic skid warehouse agent was strainghen up the load and three boxes fell to the ground from a distance of 4ft. column25: Sunoco Partners Marketing + Terminals LP by Crestwood Midstream Partners/Strobel
column168: A BNSF inbound train mechanical inspection revealed entrained tank car GATX 211559 with fresh commodity staining on its side shell. GATX 211559 was carefully set-out of its train and isolated at the facility's repair track for further inspection. GATX 211559's inspection revealed the leak source was at its manway closure with a loose (broken) securement bolt. One of six manway securement swing bolts (eyebolts) was found with a broken pivot ring at the base of this swing bolt. The break surfaces were oxidized which is indicative of an old break rather than a new break. A new swing bolt was procured, installed and the manway closure was properly secured. All spillage on GATX 211559 was cleaned with degreasing agents and wiped with absorbent pads by contract responders. Spent cleaning materials were earmarked for appropriate disposal. No ground spillage was reported.

column168: March 10, 2014:  At approximately 11AM, while conducting a routine hazardous materials inspection in Conrail's Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, FRA Hazmat Inspector R. Dedow noted tank car RTMX 2511, load, Petroleum Crude Oil (PG III), to have been offered for transportation contrary to the Hazardous Materials Regulations of the Department of Transportation, CFR Title 49.    His further inspection, and later confirmed by inspection by CR's A. Richter, Risk Management, and representatives of Hepaco-React, Conrail's environmental/hazmat emergency response contractor, noted the following:    Protective housing/bread box hinge was broken, with multiple plastic ties partially securing the housing cover to the mounting plate; said cover was also cocked and not sealing the interior valve mounting assembly as designed; once the cover was opened, it was noted the 1" air valve was partially open and valve's closure plug not even hand tight; and the 3" liquid valve was cocked and not mounted evenly on the mounting plate (lifted approximately 1/2" up on one side, allowing product to have escaped at one point during the cars movement from origination.  This product was heavy crude and had set up on the mounting plate next to and underneath the cocked liquid valve; the liquid valve's closure plug was also not even hand tight; and, one of eight manway cover securement bolts was not tool tight.    All closures were made tool tight during this inspection.  As the material was the kind that sets up similarly as Asphalt, the car was permitted to be moved onto destination (made without further incident), unloaded at the original consignee, NuStar Asphalt Refining, Paulsboro, NJ.  An OTMA was applied for by NuStar, San Antonio, TX, so car could be moved to a shop for inspection/repair/replacement of liquid valve.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: A roll-by inspection by a passing BNSF train revealed entrained three compartment covered hopper BNSF 432380 (AAR car kind C113) leaking commodity from its B-end bottom outlet. BNSF 432380 was carefully set-out of its train at the nearby set-out track at BNSF station Ricardo, NM. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspecting BNSF 432380 reported finding a crack at the upper portion of the B-end hopper outlet chute. Expandable foam was used by the responder to fill the crack which sealed it, thus preventing any further commodity release by 1715 hrs. MDT, 3/20/2014. A small amount of commodity impacting the ground under the B-end outlet was scooped up and placed into a bucket for appropriate disposal.  After being unloaded, BNSF 432380 was directed to a repair shop for permanent repairs.

column168: VEHICLE WAS RETURNING TO ALAMO, TN, FROM PICKING UP A LOAD OF DRY FERTILIZER FROM HICKMAN-FULTON CO. RIVERPORT AUTHORITY. STATE ROUTE 1099 IS A TWO-LANE ROAD; A CATTLE TRAILER WAS TRAVELING IN THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION AND WAS CROSSING THE CENTER LINE. DRIVER OF VEHICLE WAS CONCERNED ABOUT BEING STRUCK BY CATTLE TO LEAVE THE ROAD SURFACE ONTO THE SHOULDER. DUE TO MELTING SNOW ON THE ROADSIDE, THE SHOULDER WAS SOFT AND COLLAPSED UNDER THE WEIGHT OF THE TRUCK AND TRAILER CAUSING BOTH TO OVERTURN. THE FORCE OF THE OVERTURN RIPPED THE COVER FROM THE TRAILER ALLOWING THE DRY FERTILIZER PRODUCT, AMMONIUM NITRATE, TO SPILL INTO THE DITCH BESIDE STATE ROUTE 1099. NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE KENTUCKY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION'S ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CENTER AND KENTUCKY INCIDENT # 20141455 WAS ISSUED. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS NOTIFIED TO ADDRESS THE PRODUCT SPILLAGE ON THE ROADSIDE. B & P ENTERPRISES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE FROM THEIR FACILITIES IN BOTH SOUTHAVEN, MS AND NASHVILLE, TN. WHILE AWAITING FOR THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, EMPLOYEES OF HELENA CHEMICAL COMPANY OBTAINED A DUMP TRUCK LOAD OF SAND TO PLACE IN THE ROADSIDE DITCH. DUE TO A LARGE AMOUNT OF SNOW STILL ON THE GROUND AND WARMING TEMPERATURES, WATER WAS PRESENT IN THE DITCH. A SMALL AMOUNT OF AMMONIUM NITRATE ENTERED THE STANDING WATER IN THE DITCH SO THE SAND WAS USED TO PREVENT ANY DOWNSTREAM MIGRATION OF CONTAMINATED WATER. ONCE THE ENERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED, THE IMPACTED WATER IN THE ROADSIDE DITCH WAS VACUUMED UP FOR DISPOSAL. THEN, A SECOND VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO PICK UP THE LOOSE AMMONIUM NITRATE FERTILIZER FROM THE ROADSIDE.

column168: Tank car GATX 46854 at the facility's repair track for correction of an air brake mechanical defect was reported emanating a residue commodity odor. GATX 46854 was cordoned-off. Contract responders inspecting GATX 46854 reported the odor source was from the Midland 247.5 psi pressure relief valve (PRV) with deteriorated seat and stem O-rings. Suitable replacement O-rings were procured and installed. The PRV was reassembled and tested for leakage using a Photo Ionization Detector (PID) and a liquid bubble test with no evidence of leakage. Afterwards no commodity odor was detectable. Response was concluded by 1900 hrs. CDT, 3/24/2014.

column62: Valve Open; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Tank car NATX 301684 that was set-out (along with other railcars) from its train earlier in the day in a main track siding was reported with fresh commodity on its sideshell. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting NATX 301684 reported the liquid valve was not fully closed with its camlock closure cap loose. The responders immediately closed the liquid valve ending any further commodity release. The commodity outage was checked and found appropriate. All other valves and fittings were found secure. The liquid valve's camlock closure cap was missing the pin on one retainer clip which allowed the clip to fall off onto the valve housing plate leaving the camlock closure cap with only one retention clip loosely securing the closure cap. Responders applied an appropriately sized bolt in place of the missing pin and properly secured the retention clip onto the camlock closure cap. Response was concluded by 0200 hrs. CDT, 3/28/2014. Afterwards, contractors remediated ground spillage and power washed (from ground level) the spillage from the side shell of NATX 301684. Additional cleaning (degreaser application followed by a hot water pressure wash) of NATX 301684 was accomplished at the BNSF railyard in Lafayette, LA on 4/04/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF mechanical inspection of an inbound BNSF train in the railyard revealed commodity vapor emanating from the manway closure of entrained tank car UTLX 208756 with no liquid release noted. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting UTLX 208756 reported that the manway gasket was missing which allowed commodity vapors to escape at the non-sealed manway closure. A new manway nozzle gasket was applied and the manway closure was properly secured and sealed. Afterwards, no further commodity vapor release was evident at the secured manway closure.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Intermodal trailer TFVP 99406 was reported leaking an unknown liquid substance while parked in the intermodal lot. TFVP 99406 was carefully moved and isolated at the facility's containment area. Contract responders inspecting the lading within TFVP 99406 reported the leak source as one 55 gallon poly drum with inward collapsed sidewalls and a hole near the drum bottom. There was no obvious indication that this damaged drum was compromised by contact with adjacent lading or damaged by excessive weight atop the drum.  The compromised drum was placed into an overpack drum and returned to the lading after spillage inside TFVP 99406 was cleaned. Spillage impacting the cemented parking area was also cleaned.

column168: Driver was traveling northbound on county road 317. He approached the intersection of county road 317 and county road 68. column168: While driver was parked in the truck stop, a white smoke/vapor was noticed coming from the top of the trailer.  Fire Department was called out and as a precaution, part of the truck stop was evacuated.  It was found that the gasket in the dome lid of the cargo tank was allowing vapors to escape.  It will typically look like smoke when vapors from this product hit the air.  We called out an emergency response team requesting that they find a new gasket to replace the old one.  They were not able to find a replacement gasket but in the meantime, the fire department was able to tighten the dome lid enough to stop any future vapor leakage.
column169: The cargo tank is tested to make sure it will hold pressure before loading.  It is then sealed before being brought to shipper for loading.  The teflon dome gasket is new but needs to be thoroughly inspected again for any dents/crimping when the dome lid is closed and tightly sealed after loading.

column168: It was reported that a cargo tank was unloading fuel and product came back out thru the vapor system. The release impacted the concrete parking area and went into a storm drain. Absorbent pads and boom were used by the dispatched contractor to contain the release, and a vacuum truck was used to recover the release. Granular absorbents were worked into the parking area impacted by the release. All recovered materials were containerized for disposal. Duration of the release was no more than three hours.

column168: It was reported that a tote was not properly prepared for transport and suffered damage in transit. A crack in the tote released less than one gallon of product to the trailer floor. The shipper did not require the tote to be sent in a refrigerated trailer, despite the freezing point of the product being 62º. The tote was sent over the roadway in March, through Pennsylvania, with the average temperature at approximately 40 degrees. The tote cracked due to the solidification of the UN2789 Acetic Acid Glacial. No soils, storm drains or waterways were impacted by the release. Absorbent pads were used to wipe the released product off the side of the tote and the impacted areas were neutralized with sodium bicarbonate. All cleanup debris was collected and containerized for pending disposal.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 3/28/2014, VEOLIA VEHICLE #167212, LICENSE PLATE P207059(IL) BROKE DOWN IN LEE, MASSACHUSETTS AT A REST AREA. THE VEHICLE WAS HAVING TROUBLE WITH AIR PRESSURE. THE VEOLIA EMPLOYEE CALLED TO HAVE THE VEHICLE FIXED BY A THIRD PARTY TRUCK REPAIR COMPANY. THE THIRD PARTY TRUCK REPAIR PERSON ARRIVED FROM NEW YORK AND TOLD THE VEOLIA DRIVER THAT THE VEHICLE NEEDED TO BE TOWED. THE THIRD PARTY DECIDED TO TOW THE VEOLIA TRUCK WITH A TOW TRUCK AND LEAVE THE ENGINE RUNNING IN THE VEOLIA TRUCK. A SHORT TIME AFTER TOWING THE VEOLIA TRUCK, THE VEHICLES ENTERED INTO NEW YORK AND AT MILE MARKER B3 ON THE WEST BOUND SECTION OF THE NY STATE THRUWAY EXTENSION, THE VEOLIA VEHICLE ENGINE CAUGHT ON FIRE. THE TOW TRUCK OPERATOR PULLED OVER TO TRY AND PUT OUT THE ENGINE FIRE. UNABLE TO PUT OUT THE FIRE AND STATE POLICE AND LOCAL EMS RESPONDED. AS TIME PROGRESSED, THE ENGINE FIRE GOT LARGER AND SPREAD TO THE CARGO PORTION OF THE TRUCK BEING TOWED. AS THE CARGO PORTION BURNED, CONTAINERS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE COMPROMISED BY THE FLAMES AND HEAT AND RELEASED. THE FIRE OCCURRED ABOUT 9:25 AM 3/28/2014. AT 9:35 AM, THE NEW YORK STATE POLICE RESPONDED. AT 9:40 AM, VEOLIA NOTIFIED THE NEW YORK DEC TO REPORT THE EVENT. REPORT NUMBER 1312152. AT 10:25 AM VEOLIA NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER VIA PHONE THAT A REPORTABLE QUANTITY OF D001 MATERIAL HAS BEEN RELEASED. REPORT NUMBER 1078020 THE FIRE WAS COMPLETELY PUT OUT ABOUT 11:15. SITE CLEAN UP EFFORTS WERE STARTED AND COMPLETED AT THE SITE AROUND 2:15 PM. WHAT WAS LEFT OF THE TRUCK WAS TOWED TO ANOTHER THIRD PARTY TRUCK REPAIR CENTER. ON SATURDAY, 3/29/2014. THE TRUCK WAS CLEANED UP OF ALL FIRE REMNANTS IN THE CARGO PORTION OF THE VEHICLE AND A CHECK FOR ANY POSSIBLE INTACT CONTAINERS OF WASTE WAS DONE. SEVERAL CONTAINERS WERE RECOVERED INTACT WITH WASTE STILL IN THEM AND WERE DELIVERED TO THE VEOLIA OFFICE IN SCHENECTADY, NY. ALSO, ALL CLEAN UP WASTE FROM THE THRUWAY LOCATION AND THE TRUCK TOW LOCATION WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DELIVERED TO THE VEOLIA SCHENECTADY OFFICE. ALL WASTE IS BEING REVIEWED/SAMPLED AND WILL GO FOR APPROPRIATE WASTE DISPOSAL TREATMENT AS REQUIRED BY LAW.
column169: THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT APPEARS TO BE MECHANICAL FAILURE IN THE VEOLIA VEHICLE BEING TOWED WITH THE ENGINE STILL RUNNING. VEOLIA IS ASSUMING THE THIRD PARTY WILL NOT TOW ANOTHER VEHICLE WITH THE ENGINE RUNNING. ADDITIONALLY, VEOLIA WILL NOT ALLOW ANY THIRD PARTIES TO TOW ANY OF OUR VEHICLES WITH THE ENGINE STILL RUNNING. THE THIRD PARTY HAS ASSUMED ALL LIABILITY RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: While unloading two filter cake totes that were double stacked from a trailer, the material handler was unaware that the dock plate front edge shifted about 1" off the trailer; due to the weight of the forklift and totes.  As the material handler was backing up, the front edge of the dock plate caught the bottom filter cake tote.  Without the material handler noticing this shift, he continued backing up, and as a result the two filter cake totes tipped over causing some of the product to spill out inside the trailer. The foreman and supervisor were both immediately notified and the filter cake totes were brought to an upright position and the spilled material was cleaned up.
column169: Dock plate adjustment and material handler awareness training to recognize this hazard.

column168: On March 25, 2014, a 330-gallon tote experienced a damaged valve resulting in the release of UN1719, Caustic Akali Liquids to the trailer floor and asphalt below. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site. The impacted areas were neutralized. Absorbents were applied and worked in thoroughly. All impacted material was containerized.

ON 03-22-2014, I WAS ADVISED THAT YARD ASSIGNMENT WAS CONDUCTING AN INTER PLANT SWITCH AT "SAVAGE INDUSTRIES AND IN THE PROCESS OF SWITCHING CARS NOTED THAT CAR UTLX 674966 HAD SPLASHED, PRODUCT DETERMINED TO BE NA 2448 MOLTEN SULFUR OUT OF THE TOP OF THE CAR.  CREW WAS ADVISED TO STAND DOWN UNTIL MY ARRIVAL. UPON MY ARRIVAL I INSPECTED THE CAR AND NOTED THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE NOT SECURED IN ACCORDANCE WITH REGULATIONS. I SECURED MANWAY TO PREVENT FURTHER OCCURRENCE.  ADDITIONALLY I CONTACTED "SUNPRO SERVICES" A HAZMAT CONTRACTOR TO CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AND SIDE OF THE CAR. SUNPRO ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HOURS CSDT AND PROCEEDED TO CLEAN CAR AS BEST THEY CAN AND THE BALLAST AREA WAS PURGED OF SPILLED PRODUCT.  CAR WAS RE-SPOTTED IN PLANT FOR REMEDIATION
column169: ON 03-24-2014, I MET WITH MANAGER OF SAVAGE INDUSTRIES, JEFF VELTMAN AND ADVISED OF THE OCCURENCE AND SECURING CARS FOR INTER PLANT SWITCHING. JEFF ADVISED THAT IT WAS AN OVERSIGHT AND CORRECTIVE ACTION WOULD BE TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. ADDITIONALLY MANAGER WAS ADVISED TO A COMPLETE EXTERIOR CAR CLEANING PRIOR TO OFFERING THE CAR IN TRANSPORTATION.    SEE FIG. 1,2,3, & 4 ATTACHED

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 8 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: THE TOOL WAS SHIPPED TO OUR RECEIVING DOCK WRAPPED IN PLASTIC AND INSIDE A WOODEN CRATE. AFTER WORKERS REMOVED THE CRATE AND BEGAN TO UNWRAP THE PLASTIC, THEY CAME IN CONTACT WITH AN UNKNOWN LIQUID. IT WAS REPORTED THAT THE TOOL WAS SHIPPED WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF 3% HYDROGEN PEROXIDE TO INHIBIT BIOLOGICAL GROWTH IN THE INTERNAL LINES. HOWEVER, ANALYSIS OF A SAMPLE OF THE MATERIAL SHOWED THAT THE CONCENTRATION WAS SLIGHTLY MORE THAN 10%. WORKERS WHO CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE LIQUID WERE TAKEN TO THE ONSITE MEDICAL CLINIC FOR EVALUATION AND TREATMENT. THEY WERE RETURNED TO WORK ONCE THE AFFECTED AREA WAS THOROUGHLY WASHED AND RINSED. ONSITE ERT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE RESIDUE FROM THE RELEASE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE OCCURRED BECAUSE THE EQUIPMENT SUPPLIER DID NOT PROPERLY CAP THE INLET AND OUTLET LINES PRIOR TO SHIPMENT. IT IS ALSO LIKELY THAT THE EQUIPMENT SUPPLIER DID NOT PROPERLY MEASURE THE STRENGTH OF THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE FLUSHED THROUGH THE EQUIPMENT AS THE TARGET CONCENTRATION WAS 3%, BUT THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS DETERMINED TO BE 10%.
column169: INTERNAL EVALUATION OF THE ROOT CAUSE AND APPROPRIATE CORRECTIVE/PREVENTATIVE ACTIONS IS STILL ONGOING. HOWEVER, THE EQUIPMENT SUPPLIER HAS ALREADY COMMITTED-TO THE USE OF LEAK PROOF CAPS ON ALL INLET AND OUTLET LINES THAT MAY CONTAIN RESIDUAL LIQUIDS AND THEY ARE REVISING THEIR PROCEDURES FOR MONITORING THE STRENGTH OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE PRIOR TO FLUSHING IT THROUGH THE EQUIPMENT TO ENSURE IT IS LESS THAN 8%.

column168: This incident occurred while delivering propane into a residential propane tank. It is normal procedure to release a small amount of propane vapor from a bleeder screw to prevent overfilling the tank being filled. Snow had fell off the roof creating a valley between the snow back and the structure. This allow the small amount of vapor to collect. A heater exhaust greater than 10' turned on igniting the vapor and causing the propane to flash. This was quickly controlled, there where no injuries and nothing was burned, melted, or charred. The delivery vehicle was not in transit and there were no failures or defects and the flash did not happen at the vehicle. The Fire Department was called in as a safety precaution. State of Maine Propane inspectors also visited the site. There were no violation found and we were commented for our response.    Please request more details if required. I have discussed this incident with the Enforcement Officer Michael Donahue, who sent us a notification letter to report this incident.
column169: Our organization has taken this incident very seriously and additional training has been conducted...We have learned that even though everything is within code specifications that in the right conditions there are still risks.

column168: THOMAS PETROLEUM, LLC HAD A DYED DIESEL SPILL ON MARCH 22, 2014 AT APPROXIMATELY 8:25 A.M. ON HIGHWAY 64 (ALSO KNOWN AS OAK STREET) IN CONWAY, ARKANSAS (SEE ATTACHED MAP). THE ESTIMATED AMOUNT RELEASED ONTO THE SOIL WAS 100 TO 200 GALLONS.  EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT REPORTED THIS ACCIDENT TO THE STATE OF ARKANSAS ON MARCH 22, 2014. THE STATE REPORT IDENTIFICATION NUMBER IS 14-0154.  PRO AUTO CONTACTED THOMAS PETROLEUM, WHO THEN AGREED WITH PRO AUTO TO DISPATCH BIRDSONG'S ENVIRONMENTAL TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT AT APPROXIMATELY 8:49 A.M.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL VENDOR CALLED ONE SITE MANAGER/SUPERINTENDENT ALONG WITH SPILL RESPONSE TRAILER, ONE HEAVY EQUIPMENT OPERATOR, ALONG WITH TRUCK AND EXCAVATOR, AND ONE TRI-AXLE DUMP TRUCK AND DRIVER. ALL OPERATORS AND DRIVERS ARE TRAINED IN SPILL RESPONSE.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL SITE MANAGER ARRIVED ON SCENE AND MADE A COMPLETE ASSESSMENT OF WHAT WAS NEEDED TO PREVENT FURTHER CONTAMINATION.  HE PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AND BOOMS IN THE FREE PRODUCT, NOTIFIED ONE CALL TO MARK ALL THE UTILITIES, AND DISPATCHED A VACUUM TRUCK AS WELL, TO HELP VACUUM THE FREE PRODUCT OFF THE ROADWAY AND OUT OF THE ROAD DITCH ONCE HE ARRIVED ON SCENE.  THE EXCAVATOR WAS USED TO FORM EARTH DAMS TO PREVENT WATER IN THE ROAD DITCH FROM CONTINUING DOWN THE EMBANKMENT.  THEY ALL MONITORED AS THE WRECKER SERVICE WAS LIFTING AND PUMPING OFF THE DYED DIESEL PRODUCT TO ENSURE THERE WAS NO PRODUCT LEAKING AND THAT IT WOULD NOT CAUSE FURTHER CONTAMINATION.  ONCE THE WRECKAGE WAS REMOVED, THE EXCAVATION PROCESS STARTED TO REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL. AN EARTH BERM WAS FORMED AT THE END OF THE CULVERT. THE CULVERT WAS THEN FLUSHED WITH FRESH WATER AND MICRO BLAZE AS THE CONTAMINATED WATER WAS VACUUMED FROM THE OTHER END. AFTER EXCAVATING, THE AREA WAS BACK FILLED WITH CLEAN SOIL, SEEDED, AND WHEAT STRAW WAS BLOWN OVER THE AREA FOR EROSION CONTROL.  WHEAT STRAW BALES WERE PLACED IN THE ROAD DITCH TO PREVENT RUNOFF.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS BROUGHT TO THE BIRDSONG ENVIRONMENTAL’S OFFICE AND STAGED ON HEAVY MILL PLASTIC. A BERM WAS THEN FORMED AROUND THE AREA WITH EXCAVATOR, PER ARKANSAS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY REQUIREMENTS. SEE ATTACHED FOLLOWING DOCUMENTS: ANALYTICAL SDG NUMBER 1403209-01, 02, 03 IS FROM THE SITE LOCATION AFTER CLEAN-UP; ANALYTICAL SDG NUMBER 1403208-01 CONTAMINATED SOIL FOR LANDFILL DISPOSAL; PROFILE NUMBER 994228AR FOR WASTE MANAGEMENT; AND MANIFEST NUMBER 14277 FOR WASTE MANAGEMENT. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL HAS BEEN PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  IF YOU HAVE ANY FURTHER QUESTIONS, PLEASE DO NOT HESITATE TO CONTACT ME.

AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 210 GALLONS WERE RELEASED. THE FREE LIQUID IMPACTED A LARGE AREA OF SOIL AND GRAVEL. RANGE RESOURCES DISPATCHED WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP TO COMPLETE THE SOIL EXCAVATION. WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND GRAVEL AND PLACED INTO ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS FOR DISPOSAL. A TOTAL OF 16 ROLL CONTAINERS, EACH CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 15 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND GRAVEL WERE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE CLEANUP. WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT OCCURENCE.  HOWEVER, ERGON TRUCKING, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: At 12:25 pm a load of anhydrous ammonia arrived at CPS location.  The driver, an employee of STC, Inc. started unloading.  At 1:55 pm the seals blew out on the pump on STC's truck causing a release of approximately 15 gallons.  Driver shut his valves and CPS activated its safety shutoff system.  Loss was minimal, no evacuation was necessary and no one was hurt.  NRC, State and local LEPC were notified.  Clean up was minimal as it was an atmospheric discharge.

I ARRIVED AT THE HOSPITAL AROUND 9:00 AM IN THE MORNING. I PARKED ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE UNDERGROUND FILL PORT. THEN I CALLED PAT FROM THE HOSPITAL AVIATION CREW AND TOLD HIM I HAD ARRIVED. THE I PULLED MY BELLY VALVES OPEN TO LET THE FUEL SETTLE OUT FOR PAT TO TAKE A SAMPLE OF IT. ABOUT 5 TO 8 MINUTES LATER PAT SHOWED UP WITH HIS WHITE BUCKET TO SAMPLE THE JET A FUEL. WE CHECKED ALL FOUR COMPARTMENTS AND THE JET A SHOWED NO SIGNS OF WATER OR SETTLEMENTS. PAT SAID IT LOOKS GOOD GO AHEAD AND DROP IT. I FINISHED HOOKING UP MY 4" FITTINGS AND HOSE AND I STARTED DISPENSING MY COMPARTMENT 4 (2750 GAL.) PAT AND STARTED TALKING BACK AND FORTH WHILE I FINISHED HIS TICKET. WHEN COMPARTMENT 4 WAS DONE I MOVE MY 4" HOSE TO COMPARTMENT 3 (100) GAL AND I STARTED DISPENSING IT AT SOME POINT DURING THIS COMPARTMENT OR COMPARTMENT 2 (650 GAL) PAT SAID HE HAD SOMETHING TO DO AND SAID HE WOULD COME BACK TO LOCK THE FILL PORT WERE I WAS UNLOADING. I GOT ON TO MY LAST COMPARTMENT 1 (3000 GAL.) AND WHEN THAT COMPARTMENT WAS GETTING NEAR EMPTY A SECURITY GUARD YELLED YOUR SPILLING FUEL, I TURNED AROUND AND CHECKED ALL OFF MY FITTINGS AND HOSE, I TURNED BACK AROUND AT HIM AND SAID "WHAT" HE REPLIED AGAIN YOUR SPILLING FUEL ALL OVER.  I TOOK A GLANCE DOWN WERE THE GUARD WAS REALIZED WAS RUNNING DOWN THE PARKING LOT, I THEN TURNED AROUND SHUT MY API OFF GRABBED MY SPILL KIT AND TOOK OFF RUNNING TOWARD THE GUARD. FIRST THING I DID WAS FOUND THE SEWER DRAINS AND WAS GOING TO PROTECT THEM FIRST BUT TO MUCH PRODUCT WAS ALREADY RELEASED I PUT DOWN WHAT I HAD THEN WHEN LOOKING FOR THE SOURCE OF WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM. THE GUARD WAS ON THE PHONE WITH THE DES MOINES FIRE DEPARTMENT I LET HIM KNOW I THOUGHT THE RELEASE WAS 150 TO 300 GAL OF JET A SO HE COULD LET THE DMFD KNOW. I THEN HAD THE GUARD ON LOCK A PICKET FENCE AREA WERE I THOUGHT THE PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM. IN THE MINUTE TO THREE MINUTES IT TOOK TO GET IN THE PICKET FENCE AREA IT WAS DONE RUNNING OUT OF THE GROUND. A FEW MINUTES LATER THE HAZMAT AND THE DMFD ARRIVED AND TOOK OVER THE SITUATION. I GAVE THEM A B.O.L. AND LET THEM KNOW AGAIN HOW MUCH I THOUGHT WAS LOST. IT TOOK A FEW HOURS TO CLEAN UP THEN THEY DRAINED THE REST OF THE PRODUCT I HAD ON THE TRAILER, I WOULD GUESS THAT WAS MAYBE ANOTHER 10 TO 25 GAL. LEFT IN MY 4" HOSE.  AFTER THAT THE HOSPITAL SAFETY MANAGER SAID I WAS O.K. TO LEAVE I PUT MY HOSE AND ONNECTIONS AWAY AND I LEFT.  MAY 13 2014
column169: THE VEETER ROOT SYSTEM IS NOT ACCESSIBLE TO CHECKING MEASUREMENT. NEITHER IS THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK WHICH IS IN A SECURED AREA NOT ACCESSIBLE TO US. NOW I HAVE TOLD MY DRIVER NOT TO UNLOAD UNTIL WE SEE A READ OUT OF THE VEETER ROOT SYSTEM AND HAVE PHYSICAL ACCESS TO THE UNDERGROUND TANK. AT THE VEETER ROOT SYSTEM AND MEASURE THE TANK AND MADE OUT THEY ARE THE NAME THEY UNLOADING OF JET A.

column62: Rollover Accident; Inadequate Accident Damage Protection
column168: WHILE TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 65 MPH, THE CTMV HYDROPLANED AND, DUE TO THE SLOPE OF THE HIGHWAY, ROLLED OVER ABOUT 120 DEGREES TO THE RIGHT ONTO THE HIGHWAY SHOULDER.  THE CTMV CRUSHED THE GUARD RAIL AND IMPACTED THE GROUND.  THE ROLLOVER PROTECTION DEVICES (CRASH BOX TOMBSTONES) DUG INTO THE MUDDY SOIL, WHICH IMPACTED THE ACCESSORIALS IN THE DOME AREA, INCLUDING THE PRESSURE GAUGE MOUNTED TO THE PRESSURE RELIEF VENT (PRV).  THIS CAUSED THE GAUGE TO BEND AT THE THREADED CONNECTION TO THE PRV, AND HAZMAT BEGAN LEAKING THROUGH THE DAMAGED CONNECTION.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES CLOSED THE HIGHWAYS (I-59 AND US 11.)  EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE DISPATCHED TO TRANSLOAD THE PRODUCT TO A RESCUE CTMV, AND TO REMEDIATE THE IMPACTED MEDIA.  AFTER APPROXIMATELY 14 HOURS, RESPONDERS WERE ABLE TO ACCESS THE DOME AREA AND THEY APPLIED A PATCH MATERIAL TO THE DAMAGED GAUGE, WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE.  THE HAZMAT WAS TRANSLOADED TO THE RESCUE CTMV FOR SUBSEQUENT DELIVERY FOR THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DAMAGED CTMV WAS UPRIGHTED AND TOWED FROM THE SCENE.  IMPACTED MEDIA WAS REMOVED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  RESPONDING AGENCIES:  HATTIESBURG POLICE DEPARTMENT, DIXIE VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT, AND AAA AMBULANCE.    QC EVENT 40595.

column168: ON MARCH 6, 2014 AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 PM, WEBSTER & GARNER EMPLOYEE WILLIAM HARRIS, WAS DRIVING NORTH ON US 23 NEAR FENTON MICHIGAN IN A GASOLINE TANKER, WHEN SEVERAL CARS PULLED UP BESIDE THE TRUCK AND INFORMED HIM THAT HE WAS LEAKING FLUIDS.  HE PROCEEDED APPROXIMATELY 2 MILES TO A REST AREA BEFORE STOPPING TO ASSESS THE LEAK.    WHEN HE LOOKED AT THE VEHICLE, HE NOTICED A SUBSTANTIAL LEAK AND PUT A 5 GALLON BUCKET UNDER IT. HE THEN CALLED HIS BOSS JOHN KIRCHNER AT WEBSTER & GARNER TO INFORM HIM OF THE INCIDENT AND TO SEND ANOTHER TRUCK TO PUMP THE GAS INTO. AT THAT TIME, THE EMPLOYEE CALLED 911 BUT WHILE ON THE PHONE, A BYSTANDER INFORMED HIM THAT THERE WAS A STATE POLICE OFFICER IN THE REST AREA AND HE TOLD HIM TO GO GET HIM.  THE OFFICER AND MR. HARRIS USED TRAFFIC CONES TO SET A PERIMETER AND WAITED FOR THE FIRE DEPT. WHEN THEY SHOWED UP, THEY STARTED CATCHING THE GAS IN 55 GALLONS DRUMS AND SPREAD OIL DRY ON ANY GAS THAT WAS ON THE GROUND IN THE PARKING LOT.    ONCE ANOTHER TRUCK ARRIVED, THEY PUMPED OUT THE GAS IN THE #5 COMPARTMENT AND TRANSFERRED IT IN TO THE OTHER TRUCK. MR. HARRIS THEN TOOK THE BALANCE OF THE LOAD TO THE BULK PLANT. WHEN THE UNLOADING WAS COMPLETED, KESSLER ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED AND CLEANED UP THE REST AREA. THEY TRANSFERRED FUEL FROM SPILL CONTAINEMENT INTO MDOT DRUMS USED SKID STEER WITH BROOM ATTACHMENT TO SWEEP UP FLOOR DRY AND SHOVELED IT INTO DRUMS.
column169: TANK TRUCK SERVICES IN GAYLORD, MICHIGAN, REPAIRED THE PIPING AND TESTED.  THEY REMOVED THE RUBBER HOSES THAT WERE ATTACHED TO THE PIPING BECAUSE THEY SAID THAT IT HANGING SO LOW, IT COULD COLLECT SNOW AND DIRT FROM THE ROAD BUILD UP IN THE END.  REMOVING IT WOULD RAISE THE END UP TO JUST ABOVE THE AXLE HOUSING, REDUCING BUILDUP.    SINCE THE INCIDENT, WE HAVE ALSO IMPLTEMENT PROCEDURES THAT THE DRIVERS WILL GO UP TOP OF THE TRAILER AND LOOK FOR SNOW AND ICE ACCUMULATIONS DURING WINTER SEASON.

INTERVIEW CONDUCTED WITH WAYNE A. KITCHENS ON 3/5/14. DLN 92-123-3143 CO. CDL P2TXM ENDORSEMENT. ON 3/4/2014 AROUND 12:30 PM. WAYNE WAS EXITING I-70 ONTO THE EAGLE EXIT MILE MARKER 147. HE WAS PULLING INTO A LOCAL GAS STATION FOR A CUP OF COFFEE. AS HE EXITED ONTO THE ROUNDABOUT GEARED DOWN AND SLOWING DOWN. HE LOOKED TO THE LEFT AND THERE WAS A LITTLE RED CAR COMING ACROSS THE BRIDGE THAT WOULD HAVE PUT THEM IN THE ROUND ABOUT FIRST, ENTERING AT TOO HIGH OF A SPEED. HE WAS DOING APPROXIMATELY 25 MPH. HE STATED, "THAT SPEED THROUGH A ROUNDABOUT IS OK FOR A CAR, BUT NOT HIS TRUCK". AS HE CAME AROUND HIS TURN  HIS LEFT REAR DUAL TOUCHED THE SKIRT IN THE CENTER OF THE ROUNDABOUT AND LIFTED THE TRAILER. AFTER THE TRAILER LIFTED THE ANGLE AND WEIGHT CAUSED 2ND WEIGHT IT TIP OVER.  INTERVIEW BY WAYNE KITCHENS CONDUCTED BY CRYSTAL D. TBLEY 3/5/2014.

SYCAMORE TRANSPORT WAS MAKING A ROUTINE DELIVERY OF UNLEADED REGULAR GASOLINE VIA TRANSPORT TRUCK TO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK AT WELK'S SHELL, 257 E. WALNUT STREET, NAZARETH, PENNSYLVANIA. WHEN THE LOAD DROP WAS ALMOST COMPLETED (DELIVERY IS BY GRAVITY) THE TRANSPORT DRIVER LEFT THE DELIVERY HOSE CONNECTION POINT AT THE TANK FILL RISER AND RETURNED TO THE TRUCK CAB. DURING THIS TIME, THE HOSE COUPLING CONNECTION TO THE TANK FILL RISER ADAPTER CAME LOOSE AND LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 138-GALLONS OF GASOLINE.    THE GAS STATION LOT IS SLOPED TOWARDS EAST WALNUT STREET. THE GASOLINE FLOWED OFF THE LOT, ACROSS THE STREET, APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET TO THE INTERSECTION WITH SOUTH NEW STREET AND THEN INTO A STORM WATER INLET APPROXIMATELY 400 FEET FROM THE INTERSECTION.    THE STORM SEWER OUTLETS APPROXIMATELY 400 FEET TO THE EAST INTO A STONE LINED CHANNEL THAT DRAINS INTO AN ABANDONED QUARRY AND INTO A WETLANDS. THE WETLANDS AND QUARRY WERE NOT AFFECTED BY THE RELEASE.    THE LOCAL FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO PROVIDE SPILL RESPONSE AND SPREAD GRANULATED CLAY ABSORBENTS, PADS AND BOOMS TO CLEAN UP THE RELEASE.    AT THIS TIME SIXTEEN 55-GALLON 17H DRUMS CONTAINING SPENT ABSORBENT ARE STAGED ON THE GAS STATION PROPERLY. ALL DRUMS ARE PROPERLY LABELLED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE (FLAMMABILITY).    CURRENTLY BOOMS ARE PLACED AT THE STORMWATER INLET AND OUTLET AND ALONG THE STONE LINED CHANNEL. THEY ARE MONITORED AND CHANGED OUT AS NEEDED.    SLIGHT SHEENS AND GASOLINE ODOR WERE NOTED ALONG SEVERAL PLACES IN THE CHANNEL. NO FREE PRODUCT WAS FOUND. NO SHEEN WAS NOTED ON THE WATER IMPOUNDED WITHIN THE QUARRY ITSELF.    I CONTACTED DAVID MCGOVERN OF DEP (DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION) WHO WAS ONSITE FRIDAY WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED. I ASKING HIM IF HE WAS SATISFIED WITH THE CLEANUP RESPONSE SO FAR AND HE SAID YES. HE INFORMED ME THAT HE WOULD COPY ME ON ANY CORRESPONDENCE THE DEP MAY SEND TO SYCAMORE TRANSPORTATION AND THAT SCOTT BENE, A DEP WATER QUALITY SPECIALIST IN THE TANK PROGRAM WOULD BE VISITING THE GAS STATION ON MARCH 18, 2014 TO PERFORM A COMPLIANCE INSPECTION.  THE PURPOSE OF THE INSPECTION IS TO DETERMINE IF THERE MAY BEEN ANY NEGLIGENCE OF THE PART OF THE TANK OWNER THAT COULD HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO CAUSING THE SPILL.    AT THIS POINT, AS PER STANDARD PROCEDURE IN CASES LIKE THIS, DEP HAS REQUESTED SOIL BORINGS AND SAMPLING BE PERFORMED TO DETERMINE IF THERE HAVE BEEN IMPACTS TO SOILS.  AS OF THIS WRITING, THIS ACTIVITY HAS BEEN COMPLETED BUT THE LABORATORY ANALYSIS HAS NOT YET BEEN MADE AVAILABLE TO ME.
column169: DRIVER DID NOT FOLLOW REGULATIONS AND TRAINING BY LEAVING THE FILL POINT WHILE THE DELIVERY WAS IN PROCESSESS. NEED TO REINFORCE PROPER PROTOCOL WITH DRIVERS.

column168: March 21, 2014:  At approximately 1:00PM, Conductor of CR crew FL05 noted dried product residue on the side of tank car CAOX 300581, load Sodium Hydroxide, Solution (Class 8, PG II) on track 22 in River Rouge (MI) Yard.  Car only leaking under movement so car remained stationary on the track.    CR Risk Management A. Richter contacted emergency response contractor Eagle Rail Car Services to respond, inspect and mitigate the incident.    Further inspection found the 1" vapor valve, located inside a protective housing, was open, and the closure plug for said valve was not applied.  During the inspection, the valve was closed, the closure plug reapplied tool tight and protective housing cover resealed (original shipper seal(s) reported intact by the emergency response contractor during his initial inspection).  Car was deconned of previously spilled product on both sides of the car, and okayed for forwarding to originally consigned destination.

column168: ENG-1 AND C-2 RESPONDED TO 241A BLISS ST FOR A REPORT OF A POSSIBLE CHEMICAL LEAK WITH VAPOR CLOUD. UPON ARRIVAL DEP. STEVE MACHINO WAS AKLREADY ON SCENE. WE ACCESSED THE BUILDING THROUGH THE MAIN ENTRANCE AND WERE MET BY THE TERMINAL MANAGER, JOE TRAINOR. HE STATED THAT ONE OF HIS EMPLOYEES OPENED THE DOORS TO A TRAILER AT THE LOADING DOCK AND WHEN THEY DID, IMMEDIATELY SAW A GRAY VAPOR CLOUD ALONG THE TOP OF THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER, TO THE POINT WHERE THE FRONT OF THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS NOT VISIBLE AND FAINT SWEET ODOR WAS ALSO NOTICED. THEY STATED THAT THEY DID NOT SEE ANY LIQUID OR SPILLED CONTENTS ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER OR ON ZNY OF THE LOAD. THEY LEFT THETRAILER DOORS OPEN. BUT CLOSED THE ROLL UP DOOR ON THE LOADING DOCK AND TURNED ON A LARGE FLOOR FAN TO VENTILATE THE LOADING DOCK AREA. THERE WERE NO INJURIES REPORTED AND NO MEDICAL TREATMENT REQUIRED. MR. TRAINOR WAS ALSO ABLE TO PRODUCE A MANIFEST WITH THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER. IT WAS A MIXED LOAD WITH BOTH ORDINARY COMBUSTIBLES AND VARIOUS CLASS 8 CORROSIVES. DO TO THE QUANTITIES OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, THE UNKOWN PRODUCT RELEASE AND HAZARDS INVOLVED, THE REGIONAL (DISTRICT4)HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND AFTER 2 LEVEL HAZMAT RESPONSE WAS INITIATED. AN INITIAL ISOLATATION ZONE WAS ESTABLISHED AND ALL RESONNEL DENIED ACCESS TO THE AREA. WSPD WAS NOTIFIED AND 2 CRUISERS WERE BLOCK ACCESS TO THE AREAFROM VEHICLES AND OTHER TRUCKS. THE TRAILER WAS CHECKED FROM A DISTANCE FROM INSIDE THE LOADING DOCK WITH A THERMAL IMAGING CAMERA AND SHOWED READING. THE TRAILER WAS ALSO CHECKED FROM THE OUTSIDE AND NO VISIBLE LIQUID COULD BE SEEN POOLED ANYWHERE UNDERTHE TRAILER AS WELL AS NO VISIBLE VAPOR CLOUD. ENG-1 SECURED A WATER SUPPLY AT THE NEAREST HYDRANT AND A 1&3 HANDLINE WAS LAID TO THE LOADING DOCK STAIRS. MED-1 WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE FOR HAZMAT RESPONDER SUPPORT. THE DISTRICT 4 HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED WITH JOHN DEARBORN AS THE TEAM LEADER. ENG-1 PROVIDED ASSISTANCE TO THE TEAM WITH 1&3/4" hoseline for decon purposes. the hazmat team made numerous entries in an attempt to locate and identify the product involved in the leake. they were able to locate and identify the leak and the product and container were isolated and neutralized. the incident were terminated and cleanup was handed over to a cleanup contractor. all apparatus returned in service.

column168: A phenol spill of approximately 1666 gallons occurred on March 18, 2014 at  approximately10:30 PM because the phenol loading arm came out of the loading dome of rail car during the filling operation.  The spill was discovered by the shipper using a video monitor and the filling operation was immediately stopped manually.  Liquid thrust during loading in horizonal direction rotated loading arm and fill pipe out of rail car manway.  Root cause was inadequite securing of loading arm.
column169: Loading procedure was modified to require primary and secondary means of securing loading arm.  Reviewed plant wide loading procedures to assess existing loading securing procedures.  Longer term action item is to establish a standard for our loading arm stations.

column168: OR TRUCK (CARGO TANK) WAS INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT, DRIVER WAS FOLLOWING TO CLOSE TO THE CAR IN FRONT OF HIM.  THE CAR MADE A SUDDEN STOP AND OUR DRIVER SWERVED TO MISS IT AND TIPPED THE TRUCK ON ITS SIDE.  THIS CAUSED RELEASE OF DIESEL FUEL.  MOST OF THE SPILL CAME FROM THE TOP HATCH ON COMPARTMENT 2, WHICH WAS STRESSED FROM THE OVERTURN.  WE PUT OUT BOOMS AND PADS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE AND DENVER HAZMAT PUT AN ADDITIONAL CLAMP ON THE HATCH WHEN THEY ARRIVED THAT STOPPED THE LEAKING, THIS WAS ABOUT 20 TO 30 MINUTES AFTER THE INITIAL ACCIDENT.  IN ADDITION WE HAD A BULK HEAD CRACKED AND BEGUN LEAKING WHEN WE HAD THE TRUCK PULLED BACK ONTO ITS WHEELS.  WE HAD SPILL CONTAINMENT AND A VAC TRUCK IN PLACED WHEN THIS OCCURED AND RECOVERED ALL THE MATERIAL.
column169: DEFENSIVE DRIVING IF THE BIGGEST FACTOR IN PREVENTING RECURRENCE, WE HAVE USED THIS AS AN EXAMPLE FOR TRAINING OUR OTHER DRIVERS ON THE IMPORTANCE OF DEFENSIVE DRIVING, THIS WAS A COMPLETELY PREVENTABLE EVENT IF OUR DRIVER WAS FOLLOWING AT A SAFE DISTANCE.  WE WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REMIND OUR DRIVERS TO DRIVER DEFENSIVELY.  THE ADDITION WE TERMINATED THE EMPLOYMENT OF THE DRIVER WHO HAD THE ACCIDENT.

column168: TRUCK WAS TRAVELING ON BROADBRIDGE AVE IN STRATFORD. IT WAS A RAINY AFTERNOON WHILE APPROACHING A RED LIGHT A CAR CHANGED LANES IN FRONT OF TRUCK. THE DRIVER TRYED TO AVOID HITTING THE CAR AND CHANGED LANES. WHEN THE LIQUID WEIGHT SHIFTED IT AMPLIFED THE MOTION AND SENT THE TRUCK INTO A ROLL OVER. ACCORDING TO THE FIRE DEPT WHO TOOK CHARGE OF THE INCIDENT VERY LITTLE SPILLAGED OCCURED. (UNLIKE NEWSPAPER ARTICLES STATED.) THE FIRE DEPT, POLICE DEPT, EPA, AND ALL HAZMAT PERSONAL WERE AT THE SCENE DOING A SPECTACULAR JOB CONTAINING AND CLEANING UP.
column169: SUGGESTIONS WERE MADE AT THE SCENE BY SOME OF THE CLEAN UP TEAMS TO TELL OUR DRIVERS TO JUST STAY SQUARED UP.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE UNLOADING, BLOCKING OCCURRED IN THE DISCHARGE LINE. THE TRUCK DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW CORRECT PROCEDURES FOR FIXING A CLOGGED LINE. AT ABOUT 0030 HRS ON 3/1/14, WHEN THE DRIVER REMOVED THE DISCHARGED COUPLING TO EXAMINE THE PROBLEM, THE PRESSURE CAUSED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LEAD OXIDE TO BE SPRAYED OVER AN APPROXIMATE 5000 SQ FT AREA LOADING DOCK. ONCE THE SPILL OCCURRED, THE TRUCK DRIVER IMMEDIATELY INFORMED THE SUPERVISOR ON THE PREMISES. IT WAS SOON DETERMINED THAT THE SPILL NEEDED TO BE PROFESSIONALLY CLEANED AND REPORTED. A LOCAL HAZMAT CREW WAS CONTACTED TO RESPONDED ACCORDINGLY ALONG WITH IN HOUSE. ALL NECESSARY REPORTING DONE BEFORE 0200 HRS.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: According to responding CSM, the passenger baggage went through the baggage handling system from the ticketing counter into TSA area and it was cleared. Upon continuing to the make up unit (MU1) a liquid content spilled inside the passenger bag and he was immediately notified. Upon inspection of the bag by the CSM, it was discovered that a 16oz bottle of liquid monomer had spilled and that the bag contained other hazardous materials inside - (2)16oz bottles of liquid monomer, (5) 16oz bottles of barbiside, (50) 3oz bottles of nail polish, (3) 3oz bottles of biofreeze gel and (1) 16oz bottle of nail sticky base. All hazardous materials were removed from the bag and confiscated. The bag was then sent to be shrink-wrapped in order to keep it from contaminating other bags and was sent to continue travel.

Upon inspection of the bag by the CSM, it was discovered that a 16oz bottle of liquid monomer had spilled and that the bag contained other hazardous materials inside - (2)16oz bottles of liquid monomer, (5) 16oz bottles of barbiside, (50) 3oz bottles of nail polish, (3) 3oz bottles of biofreeze gel and (1) 16oz bottle of nail sticky base. All hazardous materials were removed from the bag and confiscated. The bag was then sent to be shrink-wrapped in order to keep it from contaminating other bags and was sent to continue travel.

column42: VEHICLE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED OR VEHICLE, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED
column168: This shipment sailed out of Anchorage to Tacoma Washington on the Horizon Kodiak 906S.  The container was randomly pulled and inspected for a TAG (The Adherence Group)Inspection for tariff compliance. It was discovered that the container was loaded with one vehicle and one engine with some other cargo but neither the vehicle nor the engine was declared.  This was a private citizen moving from Alaska.  I do not know if he was hazmat trained trained.  There was also a UN1075 gas grill cylinder in the shipment as well but the shipper took it out to save the expense of shipping.
column169: More attention need to be paid to "private citizens" when shipping their own belongings since they are most likely not to have had any hazardous materials training.  Customer service must inquire of them about the container contents and provide advice on proper items that need to be declared.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: Undeclared hazmat found during screening. Local FAA hazmat agents were notified.
THE PAIL WAS PLACED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR ABOUT 4 TO 5 FEET AWAY FROM A LARGE PALLET.  IN TRANSIT TO THE CUSTOMER THE PALLET SLID FORWARD PUNCTURING THE CONTAINER CAUSING THE LEAK.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN.

column168: AROUND 6:00 PM A LOAD OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA ARRIVED IN TECUMSEH TO FILL THE BULK PLANT.  AROUND 6:15PM AN IBCA SHUTTLE FILLED WITH 200 GALLONS OF WATER BURST.  THE IBCA WAS BEING USED AS A STATIONARY BLEED OFF TANK TO REMOVE PRESSURE FROM THE BULK HEAD USED TO TRANSFER ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM THE TRANSPORT TO THE BULK FACILITY.  THE AMMONIA WAS TRANSFERRED INTO THE IBCA THROUGH THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK VIA 3/8' HOSE.  IT WAS LEARNED THROUGH INTERVIEWS THAT THE BLEEDER VALVE ON THE BULK PLANT THAT RAN TO THE IBCA WAS LEFT ON DURING THE TRANSFER.  UNDER NORMAL FILLING PROCEDURE THIS VALVE IS TO BE LEFT OFF.  THE PUMPING OF ANHYDROUS DIRECTLY INTO THE IBCA CAUSED THE CONTAINER TO BECOME PRESSURIZED AND THEN BURST.  AROUND 6:20PM ALL VALVES ON THE TRANSPORT AND BULK FACILITY WERE TURNED OFF STOPPING ANY FURTHER RELEASE.  THE FOLLOWING DAY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LID HAD BEEN SECURED TO THE TOP OF THE IBCA WHICH LIMITED THE CONTAINERS ABILITY TO VENT.
column169: ANY IBCA'S USED GOING FORWARD WILL HAVE HOLES DRILLED IN THE TOPS TO VENT ANY PRESSURETHAT BUILDS UP IN THESE CONTAINERS WORKPLACE PROCEDURE WILL BE MODIFIED TO INCLUDE THELOCATION OF THE BLEEDER VALVE TO ENSURE IT GETS TURNED OFF DURING THE FILLING PROCESS.ONCE PROCEDURES ARE UPDATED EMPLOYEES WILL BE TRAINED ON THE UPDATE.
